If the student knew exactly which 4 questions were on the exam, they would study those 4.
But the problem says "Four of six... will be on the exam". This implies uncertainty about which 4.
If the student knew the 4, they would study 4.
But the question asks "how many... must be studied". This implies a strategy before knowing the outcome.
The phrasing "must be studied" suggests a guarantee.
If the student studies 4, they might miss the 2 on the exam that are in Part A.
So the answer is 5.

